    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="1247"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1247">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/381.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Bevan</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tampico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>List referred to in my July 30 was received today. Nine American companies were
                    assessed for 26,500 pesos and 32 Spanish companies for 73,000 pesos. This office
                    referred Colonel Nafarrate to Governor Caballero’s communication<note n="102"
                        xml:id="d1247fn102">See telegram of June 5, 1914, from Consul Miller,
                        printed under Forced Loans, <ref target="#pg_776">p. 776</ref>.</note> and
                    requested written statement from him advising of Government change of policy
                    regarding forced loans from foreigners since receipt of said letter. There are
                    over 100 American companies in this district, only nine appear on list, none of
                    them big oil companies. If precedent is established and Americans are compelled
                    to pay forced loans remaining ninety per cent will surely be assessed later on,
                    which will result in the closing down of the large majority of American
                    companies operating here. Will advise Department promptly result of my last
                    communication to Nafarrate.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bevan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
